\begin_layout Standard
Ben Bernanke, the former US Fed chairman, famously joked that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

The problem with QE is it works in practice, but it doesn't work in theory.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 These notes show conditions under which it works in theory.
 The goal is to identify key elasticities where the theory can predict where
 is it that it works in practice.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To motivate the notes, jokes aside, the quote is very telling of the evolution
 of monetary theory, actually.
 In response to the financial crises of 2008, Bernanke lead the Federal
 Reserve during an unprecedented program of reductin of policy rates to
 almost zero and continuously purchased private paper in an open attempt
 to preserve nancial stability and reinvigorate bank lending.
 These large purchases of assets are called quantitative easing (QE).
 During the 2008, in reaction to these unprecedented policy interventions,
 banks accumulated central bank reserves without renewing their lending
 activities.
 During the time, many practioners discussed the possibility that large-scale
 open market operations could lead to splurges in inflation.
 To some extent, Bernanke is right that many theories predict that QE does
 not work at all.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Indeed, during the time of QE, there were few models that take into account
 that monetary policy is implemented through the banking system, as occurs
 in practice.
 Instead, most macroeconomic models assumed that Central Banks control interest
 rates or monetary aggregates and abstract from how the transmission of
 monetary policy may depend on the conditions of banks.
 These lecture notes address the following questions: when is QE inflationary
 and when does it stimulate lending? Critically, to answer these questions,
 we need to be serious about how the transmission of monetary policy depends
 on portfolio decisions of banks.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These notes simplify the model of Bianchi and Bigio (2022) and extend them
 along several dimensions.
 In the model, the central bank has access to various tools.
 A first set of instruments are reserve requirements, discount rates and
 interests on reserves which in uence the costs of being short of reserves.
 This set of instruments affects the demand for reserves directly.
 This occurs through the effects on the interbank market and the liquidity
 premia learned in the previous section.
 A second set of instruments are open-market operations (OMO) and direct
 lending to banks.
 This latter set of instruments, alters the real balances of reserves in
 the system.
 Both types of instruments may carry real effects by tilting the liquidity
 management tradeoff.
 Macroeconomic effects result from their indirect eect on aggregate lending
 and interest rates.
 However, as much as a Central Bank can influence bank decisions, this influence
 depends on how easy it is for banks to substitute deposit funding and how
 easy it is for firms to substitute bank loans.
\end_layout

