\begin_layout Standard
Under the assumptions of no fiscal support and a self-funded central bank,
 we have that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ell^{g}=m
\]

\end_inset

and in differential form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d\ell^{g}=\left(\frac{dM}{M}-\frac{dP}{P^{2}}\right)\rightarrow\frac{d\ell^{g}}{\ell^{g}}=\frac{dM}{M}-\frac{dP}{P}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Bank Equilibrium Conditions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can substitute out the banks dividends and the law of motion of bank
 equity to obtain:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\max_{\ell,m,d}U\left(e^{b}(P)+d-m+\ell^{b}\right)+\beta\left(\mathbb{E}\left[R^{\ell}\ell+R^{m}m-R^{d}d+\mathbb{E}\left[\chi(s|\theta)\right]\right]\right).
\]

\end_inset

In this expression there is only liquidity risk.
 The bank's first-order conditions are given by the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\ell^{b}:\beta^{-1}U'\left(e^{b}+d-m+\ell^{b}\right) & = & R^{\ell}\label{eq:foc.loans}\\
m:\beta^{-1}U'\left(e^{b}+d-m+\ell^{b}\right) & = & R^{m}+\frac{1}{2}\underbrace{\Big[\chi^{+}+\chi^{-}\Big]}_{\text{liquidity service}\text{\ensuremath{\mathcal{L}^{m}}}}\label{eq:foc.m}\\
d:\beta^{-1}U'\left(e^{b}+d-m+\ell^{b}\right) & = & R^{d}-\underbrace{\frac{\delta}{2}\chi^{-}}_{\text{liquidity risk}\text{\ensuremath{\mathcal{L}^{d}}}}.\label{eq:foc.d}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Banks require the loan rate to be equal to the discount factor.
 We thus can express the first-order conditions of deposits and reserves
 as spreads relative to the rate on loans:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R^{\ell}=R^{m}+\frac{1}{2}\mathcal{L}^{m}
\]

\end_inset

and likewise for deposits
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R^{\ell}=R^{d}-\frac{\delta}{2}\mathcal{L}^{d}.
\]

\end_inset

The bank must be indifferent between making loans and issuing reserves on
 the margin.
 Thus, the rate on reserves plus the liquidity service provided by them
 must equal the rate on loans.
 Likewise, the rate on deposits minus a compensation for the liquidity risk
 they imply.
 Let be explicity about what variables enter the liquidity serives (or liquidity
 yield) function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{L}^{m}\left(\theta,P\right)=\frac{1}{2}\left(\chi^{+}\left(\theta,P\right)+\chi^{-}\left(\theta,P\right)\right).
\]

\end_inset

The function depends on prices because the rates 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{w}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{m}$
\end_inset

 are real rates, where policy sets 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{w}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

