\end_inset

.
 We can express it in it's differential form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d\ell=d\ell^{g}+d\ell^{b}.
\]

\end_inset

Thus, we can express this equation again as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\ell}{\ell}=\frac{\ell^{g}}{\ell}\frac{d\ell^{g}}{\ell^{g}}+\frac{\ell^{b}}{\ell}\frac{d\ell^{b}}{\ell^{g}}
\]

\end_inset

or more condendsedly as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\ell}{\ell}=\left(1-\zeta^{b}\right)\frac{d\ell^{g}}{\ell^{g}}+\zeta^{b}\frac{d\ell^{b}}{\ell^{g}}.
\]

\end_inset

where we define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\zeta^{b}=\frac{\ell^{b}}{\ell},
\]

\end_inset

as the share of private credit loans held by banks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Likewise, we can apply the differential form to the budget constraint of
 the bank:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{d\left[div\right]}{div}=\omega_{e}\frac{e^{b}'(P)P}{e^{b}(P)}\frac{dP}{P}+\omega_{m}\frac{dm}{m}+\omega_{\ell}\frac{d\ell^{b}}{\ell^{b}}+\omega_{d}d\left[\frac{d^{b}}{d^{b}}\right],\label{eq:diff.budget}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega_{e}=\frac{1}{div/e^{b}(P)},\text{ }\omega_{m}=-\frac{m/e^{b}(P)}{div/e^{b}(P)},\text{ }\omega_{\ell}=-\frac{\ell^{b}/e^{b}(P)}{div/e^{b}(P)},\text{ and }\omega_{d}=\frac{d/e^{b}(P)}{div/e^{b}(P)}.
\]

\end_inset

For references below, I use:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\epsilon_{P}^{b}=\frac{e^{b}'(P)P}{e^{b}(P)}
\]

\end_inset

to denot the exposure of bank equity to inflation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Th coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{e}$
\end_inset

 represents the bank's inverse dividend rate; the subsequent coefficients
 are the portfolio weights relative to the the dividend rate.
 This equation governs the payout rate.
 Also, note that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega_{e}+\omega_{m}+\omega_{\ell}+\omega_{d}=1.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, we work with the first-order condition system (
