LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:foc.loans"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:foc.d"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) in its differential form.
 For example, working on equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:foc.loans"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) leads to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
dR^{\ell}=\beta^{-1}U''\left(div\right)d\left[div\right].
\]

\end_inset

Thereby, manipulating terms:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
dR^{\ell}=\beta^{-1}U'\left(div\right)\frac{U''\left(div\right)div}{U'\left(div\right)}\frac{d\left[div\right]}{div}.\label{eq:diff.loans}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Thus, re-arranging terms we have that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dR^{\ell}}{R^{\ell}}=-\frac{1}{\psi}\frac{d\left[div\right]}{div}
\]

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{U''\left(div\right)div}{U'}=-\frac{1}{\psi}.
\]

\end_inset

represents the intertemporal-elasticity of sbustitution for divdends.
 Here, there are no wealth effects so higher rates induce a decrease in
 dividends—or can represent equity injections if we transform dividends
 to be net-dividends.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In turn, we have that if we replace the loan clearing condition into the
 loan demand equation, we obtain:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{dR^{\ell}}{R^{\ell}}=\frac{1}{\epsilon^{B}}\left[\left(1-\zeta^{b}\right)\frac{d\ell^{g}}{\ell^{g}}+\zeta^{b}\frac{d\ell^{b}}{\ell^{g}}\right].\label{eq:diff.loanrate}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Hence, combining (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:diff.budget"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:diff.loanrate"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:diff.loans"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), we obtain:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{\epsilon^{B}}\left[\left(1-\zeta^{b}\right)\frac{d\ell^{g}}{\ell^{g}}+\zeta^{b}\frac{d\ell^{b}}{\ell^{g}}\right]=-\frac{1}{\psi}\left[\omega_{e}\epsilon_{P}^{b}\frac{dP}{P}+\omega_{m}\frac{d\ell^{g}}{\ell^{g}}+\omega_{\ell}\frac{d\ell^{b}}{\ell^{b}}+\omega_{d}\frac{d\left[d\right]}{d}\right]\label{eq:diff.fundamental.loans}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where I also used 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell^{g}=m,$
\end_inset

 following the earlier the assumption of no fiscal support.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider now the differential form of the reserve demand equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:foc.m"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
dR^{\ell}=\overbrace{\left[\frac{1+i^{m}}{\mathbb{E}\left[P\right]}P+\mathcal{L}^{m}\left(\theta\left(M/P\right),P\right)\right]}^{R^{\ell}}\frac{dP}{P}+\mathcal{L}^{m}\left(\theta\left(M/P\right),P\right)\frac{\mathcal{L}_{\theta}^{m}\left(\theta\left(M/P\right),P\right)\theta}{\mathcal{L}^{m}\left(\theta\left(M/P\right),P\right)}\frac{d\theta}{\theta}.
\]

\end_inset

This equation uses that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R^{m}=\frac{1+i^{m}}{\mathbb{E}\left[P'\right]}P,
\]

\end_inset

and treats expectations as constant.
 Hence:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
dR^{m}=\frac{1+i^{m}}{\mathbb{E}\left[P'\right]}P\frac{dP}{P}.
\]

\end_inset

Likewise, the discount window rate is affected:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
dR^{dw}=\frac{1+i^{dw}}{\mathbb{E}\left[P'\right]}P\frac{dP}{P}.
\]

\end_inset

Since each 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset

 term has the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\chi=\left(R^{dw}-R^{m}\right)g\left(\theta\right).
\]

\end_inset

It must be the case that:s
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d\chi=\left(R^{dw}-R^{m}\right)g\left(\theta\right)\frac{dP}{P}.
\]

\end_inset

Hence, the effect of prices on the liquidity premium is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d\mathcal{L}^{m}=\mathcal{L}^{m}\left(\theta\left(M/P\right),P\right)\frac{dP}{P}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Re-arranging terms, we obtain:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dR^{\ell}}{R^{\ell}}=\frac{dP}{P}+\frac{\mathcal{L}^{m}\left(\theta\left(M/P\right),P\right)}{R^{\ell}}\frac{\mathcal{L}_{\theta}^{m}\left(\theta\left(M/P\right),P\right)\theta}{\mathcal{L}^{m}\left(\theta\left(M/P\right),P\right)}\frac{d\theta}{\theta}.
\]

\end_inset

The rate on loans increases in real terms as the valuation of reserves increases.
 A response of current prices decreases inflation, so it provokes an increase
 in the loans rates.
 The second term captures how the liquidity yield, relative to the loan
 rate reponds to the change in the interbank-market conditions.
 Now recall that applying the differentials to the market tightness leads
 to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\theta\equiv\frac{\delta d-\ell^{g}}{\ell^{g}}
\]

\end_inset

where I again used 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell^{g}=m$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, we have that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
d\theta & = & -\theta\left[\frac{d\ell^{g}-\delta d\left[d\right]}{\delta d-\ell^{g}}+\frac{d\ell^{g}}{\ell^{g}}\right]=-\theta\left[\frac{1}{\delta d-\ell^{g}}+\frac{1}{\delta d+\ell^{g}}\right]\left[\ell^{g}\frac{d\ell^{g}}{\ell^{g}}\right]+\theta\left[\frac{\delta d}{\delta d-\ell^{g}}\right]\frac{d\left[d\right]}{d}.\\
 & = & -\theta\left[1+\frac{1}{\theta^{-1}}\right]\frac{\ell^{g}}{\delta d+\ell^{g}}\frac{d\ell^{g}}{\ell^{g}}+\theta\left[\frac{\delta d}{\delta d-\ell^{g}}\right]\frac{d\left[d\right]}{d}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Thus, we have that the market tightness reponds to the open-market operation
 by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\theta}{\theta}=-\left[1+\frac{1}{\theta^{-1}}\right]\frac{\ell^{g}}{\delta d+\ell^{g}}\frac{d\ell^{g}}{\ell^{g}}+\left[\frac{\delta d}{\delta d-\ell^{g}}\right]\frac{d\left[d\right]}{d},
\]

\end_inset

and obserive that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\ell^{g}}{\delta d+\ell^{g}}$
\end_inset

 is the ration of deficits in the interbank market relative to surplusses.
 For convenience, define the elasticity of the liquidity yield to the market
 tightness, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{\epsilon}_{\theta}^{\mathcal{L}^{m}}=\frac{\mathcal{L}_{\theta}^{m}\left(\theta\left(M/P\right),P\right)\theta}{\mathcal{L}^{m}\left(\theta\left(M/P\right),P\right)}.
\]

\end_inset

From here we obtain the exposure of the liquidity premium to the change
 in real balances:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\epsilon_{\ell^{g}}^{\mathcal{L}^{m}}\equiv-\mathbb{\epsilon}_{\theta}^{\mathcal{L}^{m}}\left[1+\frac{1}{\theta^{-1}}\right]\frac{\ell^{g}}{m+\delta\bar{d}}.
\]

\end_inset

and likewise, we have that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\epsilon_{d}^{\mathcal{L}}\equiv\mathbb{\epsilon}_{\theta}^{\mathcal{L}^{m}}\frac{\delta d}{\delta d-\ell^{g}},
\]

\end_inset

This elasticities are clearly negative and positive respectively because
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{\epsilon}_{\theta}^{\mathcal{L}}<0$
\end_inset

.
 To finalize the differential representation, we use (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:diff.loanrate"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula 
